Right-wing populists win in Austria, 29 percent overall
The first preliminary results of the Austrian early parliamentary elections on Sunday show a marked weakening of the two parties in the grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, was seriously shaken, suffered particularly heavy losses.
In contrast, the head of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the provincial governor of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing a victorious return to national politics.
Preliminary results show the country's strongest party, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ), with 29.8 percent of the vote, but a loss of 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last election in 2006.
Even worse, the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote, with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results in the post-war history of both major parties in Austria, and especially for the People's Party, which has been promoting early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a significant advantage over the SPÖ in public opinion polls.
But the voters clearly punished him for letting the government fail.
In the first reactions to the results, speculation was heard about the possible resignation of party leader and current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the party leadership.
This development would probably facilitate the increasingly likely outcome of the election, i.e. the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and ÖVP.
Given the strength of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ) gained 18% of the vote and the BZÖ 11% of the vote - the Social Democrats, however, expressed fears about a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed to a coalition government with the populists (the FPÖ was then still united, but in 2005 it left BZÖ), which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared his willingness to cooperate with any party and I assume that he can return to Vienna to national politics, obviously expects this solution.
The Greens were also elected to parliament, but they lost some popularity and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties passed the four percent threshold and did not enter Parliament.
