Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon is a reality
Long before Turkey's intention to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deeply into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 paces from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial quest.
The Hydarpasha Railway Station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the travel books say.
The building surrounds the end of the platforms, with a tower at each outer corner, and looks like some kind of German country town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is a little rusty.
However, a look inside the vaulted ticket office reveals the extent of the business that was going on in the westernmost gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquest, wanted to use this railroad from Damascus to Baghdad to what is now Saudi Arabia to achieve its ambitions to conquer the Middle East.
German efforts to conquer the world collapsed during World War I.
His railroad was attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded, destroying the building's beautifully crafted roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling into ruin, and it is well past history.
At the same time, today, as the railway gateway to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, it serves - at least in a symbolic sense - as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new politics is the metal of commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to gauge the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Suat Kiniklıoglu, a member of the Turkish parliament.
The next morning, after a ten-and-a-half-hour blackout that set the tone for the famous documentary film about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, a new city that was meant to be a symbol of the new secular state that was turning its back on the past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has raised some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern, stone and steel building built specifically for this purpose, which is located in a developing suburban area, between shopping malls and semi-finished coffee houses, where middle-managers in suits - men and women alike - meet to do business early in the morning.
Suat Kinyiklioglu would have been a politician of the center-right in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit and tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy aims to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset the order", he said.
Turkey is isolated from its rear.
He had to turn east and west at the same time today.
He didn't have a choice.
It had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later he will have to make a choice?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to be put in the way".
He then emphasised what almost everyone I spoke to here has said, almost in a roundabout way: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea are as much to the advantage of Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey's own advantage.
It was as if they were trying to convey the message that, figuratively speaking, all of Europe, including Turkey, could reach Asia and the Middle East by those railways going east.
When I was at the Hydarpasha station again, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conur, the two German gentlemen who had watched the construction of this magnificent structure 100 years ago.
How surprised you would be to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East are now largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I was waiting in the harbor for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that back then, Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe".
At least at the time, there was no question as to which continent would claim this exciting land.
