The collision-avoidance 'snow'
For the development of its accident-prevention technologies, Nissan has drawn inspiration from nature, specifically from the world of bees, for its new invention.
A Japanese company has designed a robot that mimics the flight of bees and avoids accidents.
It may be that the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C will be the first step in the development of collision-avoidance technologies.
Engineers from the Advanced Technology Center of Nissan Motor Co. in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center of the renowned University of Tokyo, Japan, built this little robot.
As defined by Kazuhiro Doi, the Brand Director of Technology PR and Research and Development, the BR23C represents a further extension of Nissan's four-level safety cover.
The robot will enhance the company's ability to avoid collisions.
As they fly, each bee forms an oval-shaped personal space, very similar to a Nissan safety helmet.
But even more important is the bee's complex eye, which sees in all directions at more than 300 degrees, allowing it to fly unobstructed in its own personal space.
To replicate the function of the compound eye, engineers designed a device called a laser range finder.
The instrument identifies obstacles within a range of up to 2 metres in front of BR23C at 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts into a collision avoidance operation.
"Once the obstacle is detected, the little robot imitates the movement of the bee and immediately changes direction by shifting the wheels at a greater or lesser angle to avoid the collision.
The system is most distinguished from the currently available instruments by the fact that in this case the avoidance manoeuvre is carried out completely automatically.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the bypass manoeuvre cannot be directed up or down, nor across, but only in two dimensions and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and manner as in the case of bees.
That's why Nissan has added a rotation function to the robot to avoid collisions, in addition to acceleration and deceleration.
"This machine only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
It doesn't need to store data, and it doesn't need intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can run without interruption with just a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabytes, but we're not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of technology for the immediate prevention of collisions, which Nissan estimates could be introduced in series production cars within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, it may also be possible to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to help the car reach its destination by avoiding obstacles in the road.
