Part of Fortis Bank nationalised by the Benelux governments
The Benelux countries are helping to partially nationalise the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, which was the first European bank to fall into difficulty as a result of the US credit crisis. The three countries are providing a total of EUR 11.2 billion in support to a financial and insurance institution with interests in Hungary.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments reached agreement on the matter at the end of the week at the highest level, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, Fortis Bank is the first major crisis to hit the waves in the context of the international financial crisis that has been raging for more than a year, and the decisions taken in its case can therefore be considered precedent-setting in some respects.
The decision, which was made on Sunday night, will see all three states buy up nearly half (49%) of the bank's existing assets there.
The bank will probably sell some of its holdings, including in particular the activities, mainly insurance, acquired from the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
Fortis' stock began to plunge last week, and the second half of the week was marked by a serious crisis at the institute.
But analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to be allowed to fail.
The company's stock just dropped about 12 percent on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the stock has dropped by more than two-thirds.
At current share prices, the total market capitalisation of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but the company's managers consider this to be unrealistic.
The company's management blamed the collapse of Fortis shares on overseas market uncertainties related to the adoption of a $700 billion U.S. package.
The stock was up a little bit Monday.
On Friday, a new CEO was appointed to head the bank in the person of Filip Dierckx.
The bank has been looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors need not worry, they will not lose their money.
There's no panic among the bank's customers, no raids on the drawers.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches and has also acquired leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with an applicant based on people's drug purchase records.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program that makes the use of prescription data in all cases subject to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in independent hands, or we're leaving the chicken-killing to the fox", says Richard Dicket, who developed a program to track prescriptions for drugs, according to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies may determine the amount of the premium and the amount of the indemnity if the health of the customer is concerned, and if the risk is considered too great, they may not take out insurance.
In the past, a person was sent for a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the examination was completed.
Dick had a much cheaper system ten years ago: he could easily obtain from pharmacies the ID number of a customer, the medications that the customer had purchased in the past year and a half, and from this program he could infer what disease he had and what his medical condition was.
For example, if you are taking high-dose cholesterol-lowering drugs on a regular basis, it indicates that you have practically untreatable high blood-fat levels, which immediately places you in a higher risk category.
There are several variants of the program, some of which also include a risk factor, so that the insurer has little to do other than the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include the fact that some drugs can be used for more than one purpose, such as certain compounds that can be used to treat migraines or hot flashes, but also to treat depression.
The latter is considered a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, the former not.
Companies have been set up to collect and process the data, and they ask for the patient's consent before they collect the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now required to do so by the authorities, although no penalty has been imposed for their failure to do so.
Some companies are now processing lab tests and linking them to drug data to provide a more accurate picture of patients' health.
As more companies gain access to data, it becomes increasingly difficult to control its use.
There's a separate health data protection law, but it only covers health care providers and insurance companies.
Congress is considering a bill that would give the government control over companies that specialize in data.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough, so he develops his program, which would link the transfer of data to the express consent of the data subject.
It is another matter that the person concerned cannot possibly refuse to pay the contribution, otherwise the insurers will not sign a contract with him.
So the roosters are, to some extent, still at the mercy of the fox.
