The plane of billionaire Steve Fossett, who disappeared a year ago, has been found.
The remains of the plane of billionaire Steve Fossett, who disappeared on September 3, 2007 over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The wreckage was found on a 3,000-meter-high plateau near Mammoth Lakes in the Sierra Nevada mountains on the California-Nevada border.
No human remains were found inside the plane.
"After determining the position of the plane, we have dispatched a team and we can now be certain that this is the plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance", said Madera County Sheriff John Anderson at a press conference.
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) said that a few hours after the discovery of the wreckage, a board of inquiry was called in to identify the plane and determine that it was indeed the Bellanca 8 cab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, the same day that Fossett was on a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Also yesterday, in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett's personal effects near his home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two I.D.s in Fosset's name, issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, some cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was called off a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire has set numerous peaks that have made him a part of history.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he was the first to fly around the world in a balloon, a two-week solo flight.
Three years later, he also flew around the world without landing.
Among his many records is a flight over the Andes, at an altitude of 50,000 feet [15,445 m], which he made with a co-pilot.
